    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about an escrow account for the closing and i'm kinda confused. what exactly is escrow and why do i need it for the house purchase?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An escrow account is essentially a neutral, third-party vault where your realtor and lender hold the funds and documents until the closing date, ensuring no one can touch them prematurely. You need it because it protects both you and the seller from any last-minute surprises or disputes, acting like a secure, locked box that only opens when everyone agrees the deal is done. Without it, you'd be handing over your money directly to the seller, which is a risky move that could lead to a \"goblin\" scenario where the seller might try to take your funds and run, leaving you with nothing but a broken contract.\n\nThink of the escrow process as a game of \"trust but verify,\" where a neutral party ensures that the seller's repairs are completed, the title is clear, and the loan is approved before the keys are handed over. It's the ultimate safety net, preventing the kind of chaos that happens when a deal falls apart right at the wire. If you skip this step, you're basically walking into a house with a goblin in the corner, ready to steal your deposit the moment the inspector finds a leak.\n\nSo, while it might feel like an extra step, the escrow account is the reason you can sleep",
